</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bionomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bionomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<bibRefCitation author="Pearce, EJ" journalOrPublisher="Royal Entomological Society, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" publicationUrl="http://www.royensoc.co.uk/sites/default/files/Vol04_Part09.pdf" refId="B166" refString="Pearce, EJ, 1957. ColeopteraPselaphidae. Handbooks for the identification of British insects (Vol. IV), part 9. Royal Entomological Society, London" title="ColeopteraPselaphidae. Handbooks for the identification of British insects (Vol. IV), part 9." url="http://www.royensoc.co.uk/sites/default/files/Vol04_Part09.pdf" year="1957">Pearce (1957)</bibRefCitation>
writes that this species can be collected from the base of grasses and under stones along sandy river banks and in flood debris in Britain. Unlike other European (
<bibRefCitation author="Pearce, EJ" journalOrPublisher="Royal Entomological Society, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" publicationUrl="http://www.royensoc.co.uk/sites/default/files/Vol04_Part09.pdf" refId="B166" refString="Pearce, EJ, 1957. ColeopteraPselaphidae. Handbooks for the identification of British insects (Vol. IV), part 9. Royal Entomological Society, London" title="ColeopteraPselaphidae. Handbooks for the identification of British insects (Vol. IV), part 9." url="http://www.royensoc.co.uk/sites/default/files/Vol04_Part09.pdf" year="1957">Pearce 1957</bibRefCitation>
) or North American (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4243.1.6" author="Owens, BE" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="139 - 152" refId="B157" refString="Owens, BE, Carlton, CE, 2017. Seven new species of Bibloplectus Reitter (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Pselaphinae) from Eastern United States with notes on distributions of previously described species. Zootaxa 4243: 139 - 152" title="Seven new species of Bibloplectus Reitter (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Pselaphinae) from Eastern United States with notes on distributions of previously described species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4243.1.6" volume="4243" year="2017">Owens and Carlton 2017</bibRefCitation>
) species of the genus, it does not occur in deep leaf litter or damp moss. Both 
<bibRefCitation author="Pearce, EJ" journalOrPublisher="Royal Entomological Society, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" publicationUrl="http://www.royensoc.co.uk/sites/default/files/Vol04_Part09.pdf" refId="B166" refString="Pearce, EJ, 1957. ColeopteraPselaphidae. Handbooks for the identification of British insects (Vol. IV), part 9. Royal Entomological Society, London" title="ColeopteraPselaphidae. Handbooks for the identification of British insects (Vol. IV), part 9." url="http://www.royensoc.co.uk/sites/default/files/Vol04_Part09.pdf" year="1957">Pearce (1957)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Besuchet, C" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique Suisse" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="153 - 209" refId="B17" refString="Besuchet, C, 1955. Monographie des Bibloplectus et Pseudoplectus palearctiques. Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique Suisse 28: 153 - 209" title="Monographie des Bibloplectus et Pseudoplectus palearctiques." volume="28" year="1955">Besuchet (1955)</bibRefCitation>
state that the species is infrequently collected but this may be due to the extremely small size and unknown microhabitat requirements. One of the Canadian specimens was collected with a Malaise trap on farmland, the other was extracted from soil and leaf litter from a mixed habitat of farmland and forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Only female specimens were available from the Nearctic, but they share identical barcode haplotypes with a specimen of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Bibloplectus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bibloplectus minutissimus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutissimus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bibloplectus minutissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sampled from Germany. They were also morphologically consistent with the diagnostic characters listed above. In the Palaearctic fauna, females of this species can be recognized by a combination of small size, pale body, temples clearly longer than eyes, and apical tergite produced into a long spine (
<bibRefCitation author="Besuchet, C" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique Suisse" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="153 - 209" refId="B17" refString="Besuchet, C, 1955. Monographie des Bibloplectus et Pseudoplectus palearctiques. Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique Suisse 28: 153 - 209" title="Monographie des Bibloplectus et Pseudoplectus palearctiques." volume="28" year="1955">Besuchet 1955</bibRefCitation>
). In the Nearctic region, males are needed for an accurate morphological identification (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler, DS" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="503 - 529" refId="B38" refString="Chandler, DS, 1990. The Pselaphidae (Coleoptera) of Latimer county, Oklahoma, with revisions of four genera from eastern North America. Part I. Faroninae and Euplectinae. Transactions of the American Entomological Society 115: 503 - 529" title="The Pselaphidae (Coleoptera) of Latimer county, Oklahoma, with revisions of four genera from eastern North America. Part I. Faroninae and Euplectinae." volume="115" year="1990">Chandler 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4243.1.6" author="Owens, BE" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="139 - 152" refId="B157" refString="Owens, BE, Carlton, CE, 2017. Seven new species of Bibloplectus Reitter (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Pselaphinae) from Eastern United States with notes on distributions of previously described species. Zootaxa 4243: 139 - 152" title="Seven new species of Bibloplectus Reitter (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Pselaphinae) from Eastern United States with notes on distributions of previously described species." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4243.1.6" volume="4243" year="2017">Owens and Carlton 2017</bibRefCitation>
) as many undescribed species are still expected.
</paragraph>
